[The concerning epizootic situation in the region is adequately covered in the above item; FAO and the UK sponsors deserve to be praised for the steps undertaken to enhance the required control measures.

Among the 3 transboundary diseases mentioned, the most recent introduction -- namely LSD -- deserves special attention, in view of its potential to continue its spread eastwards in Asia and westwards into the Balkans, affecting the susceptible cattle population. The inclusion of Iraq among the list of countries already affected deserves to be officially confirmed: Iraq, similarly to Syria, has not reported LSD (yet) to the OIE.

LSD has been reported in the past in captive wildlife in Oman, Saudi Arabia and UAE; an RFI for the situation in domestic cattle is pending (see ProMED-mail post 20130724.1842366).

For LSD, live attenuated vaccines only are available, using either a specific lumpy skin disease virus or a cross-protecting sheep and goat pox virus. It will be helpful to obtain information about the vaccine type (strain) applied in Lebanon.

A wide-scale comparative field trial, applying 2 vaccines (sheep pox, LSD) has been undertaken in Israel during 2013. Results, in case available, may provide useful data for other countries in the region. - Mod.AS]
